<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910123-0047</DOCNO><DOCID>910123-0047.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Martin Marietta Corp.:   Quarterly Profit Fell 22%;   $78 Million Reserve Cited</HL><DATE>01/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   ML</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><LP>   Martin Marietta Corp. said fourth-quarter earnings dropped22% because it took a $78 million reserve against possibleloss of its mobile air defense and antitank systems program.   The Bethesda, Md., aerospace and defense company saidearnings fell to $57.2 million, or $1.17 a share, from $73.5million, or $1.41 a share. Sales slipped 3.7% to $1.56billion from $1.62 billion.</LP><TEXT>   Martin Marietta said the $78 million reserve, which wastaken as a result of uncertainties stemming from a two-yeardelay by the Army on full production of the airdefense-antitank systems, covers capitalized preproductioncosts. This reserve is intended to insulate future earningsif the program is discontinued, the company said.   In contrast with the fourth quarter, Martin Marietta's netincome for the full year rose 6.7% to $327.6 million, or$6.52 a share, from $306.9 million, or $5.82 a share. Salesincreased 5.7% to a record $6.13 billion from $5.8 billion.</TEXT></DOC>